Long time Fenix user and recently updated to Fenix 2. I was very happy with 
the upgrade but in the process came across Talon in the play store which 
has a higher rating score. I thought I'd give it a try. I ditched Fenix 2 
to give Talon a try. What a mistake that was. Fenix 2 is much much more 
refined than talon in its ability to customize the UI as well as handle 
notification. With Fenix 2 navigating through the timeline is reliable, 
keeps tour last read place and runs buttery smooth. On the other hand Fenix 
2's main competitor Talons look and feel was impressive at first, but after 
a weeks use I found it to be quirky and found myself getting lost in 
tweets. This was never an issue with Fenix or Fenix 2. I found myself 
missing many tweeks, Icould not tell if my timeline was up to date and when 
I refreshed (my favorites) I would be taking to the top of the list losing 
my previous location in my timeline (yes top down mode was disabled, and I 
got confirmation from the developer that favorites does not save your last 
read location in timeline). Notifications are also lacking in Talon. though 
can be triggered on many different parameters its very rudimentary in 
implementation always taking you to the top of the list. In addition to 
that when it takes you to the list that triggered the notification it would 
continue to load older tweets in the timeline causing the the whole UI to 
get jittery and slow down. I'm made the switch back to Fenix 2 and could 
not be happier with this awesome app. It's very refined and has a feature 
set that is very well thought out.

Overall the original and this updated version are my favorite Twitter app and while I feel this improves on the original in many ways there are a couple of issues. The first is minor, one of my favorite features of the original was the ability to attach images from other apps besides the picture app. So I could directly attached pictures from Dropbox or Google drive to a tweet.  The much bigger issue that's actually heavily making me consider asking for a refund is that this app uses a cripplingly large amount of data more than the original app did. I can only assume that it's automatically downloading pictures and videos before I even view them. In the previous app I would use maybe 100 to 150 megabytes of data a month. Every month since I've had this app it alone uses over 400 megabytes. It's using two to three times as much data for no reason and it is costing me money. Please fix this ASAP. The app won't notify of new tweets unless you disable battery optimization for the app on Android Oreo, dropping a star for every release that doesn't fix this
replyContent:
Unfortunately there's no way around this - Oreo battery optimizations aggressively limits apps background activity. The proper solution would be to have push notifications, but new Twitter 3rd party apps cannot implement those.
You can enable the option to intercept the official app notifications as an alternative.
